Kimes Elementary School
August 25 at 7:58 PM ¬∑

Good Evening Everyone! I was just thinking of what a whirlwind this first week and a half has been as a new principal at Kimes during our "new normal." As I walked around today you have to know how amazing your child's teacher is.
PE classes and Speech sessions taking place outside, Full remote teachers engaging their students online including Art, Music, and PE teachers.
Our in class teacher's keeping the rooms clean and making learning and wearing masks fun. If you haven't thanked your child's teacher, please do as they are truly gifted and amazing!

A big thanks to you as parents for putting your child's education on the forefront as you navigate our "new normal."

We made it to Friday!!! Just to calm some worries, we keep all students in cohorts. They do everything together, eat, recess, bathroom breaks. They are not physically close to others. The reason for this is that when we get a positive case we only have to quarantine a small amount of kids and staff. Which we just did. That way we can keep doing what we love, Teaching Your Kids!

Kimes Elementary School was celebrating success.
August 18 at 9:03 PM ¬∑

Good Evening Dragons! We did it, had a successful and safe A and B days and our full remote learners are working so hard!!
A few reminders:
-No E-Learning or Full Remote Learning tomorrow, teachers will be prepping for E-Learning to begin on August 26th. This means that A/B students and full remote learners will ALL be E-Learning on Wednesdays. Please be looking for communication from your teacher for the 26th.
-If you have a transportation change please call or email the office by 1:00 so we can notify the teacher.
-Thursday and Friday is regular dismissal at 3:05 for our A/B learners.
I appreciate all of your patience as we work through making our school safe, but still fun for our Kime's superheroes. Your children truly have been amazing with their masks and social distancing.
Sincerely, Mrs. Ketcham

Don't forget tomorrow is your chrome book pick up and meet your teacher day. Please make sure you wear masks and only one parent is in attendance with their student. Temperatures will be taken at the front doors and then you will proceed into the gym and we will direct you to your remote teacher's table to get logged into your chrome book. LAST NAMES STARTING WITH L-Z please arrive promptly at 4:00.

B students first day is August 18th.

Looking forward to meeting everyone!

text:
Due to the change in the guidance received yesterday from the Illinois State Board of Education, we will now offer a remote only option for students in PK-8. Families will need to sign up for the first trimester by filling out the survey on this link: https://forms.gle/nKQPAPUrfiHAMp6F7. You do not need to do anything if you want to keep the "A" and "B" schedule. This must be filled out by end of the day Monday, so that we can begin making assignments. You must fill out online registration in Skyward if you haven't already done so. Please complete this form by end of the day Monday, July 27th to receive online learning Thanks!

shared_text:
Kimes Elementary School
July 7 at 6:22 PM ¬∑

Dear Kimes Parents and Students,

I would like to introduce myself as your new principal at Kimes Elementary School. I am a wife, mother of three, and I have been an educator for 19 years. It's been my goal to lead and become a principal and am so fortunate to start that journey here at Kimes. Everyone I have talked with on the phone and met in person have welcomed me with open arms and I couldn't be happier.

I understand that the school year will look a little different this year, but that won't stop the entire staff from making it the best year yet. As a mom and educator I worry just as much as you do so know that I am a phone call or email away to ease those worries. Can't wait to see our Dragons, the office is pretty quiet right now! Stay tuned for some more staff and school updates.

Sincerely, Mrs. Ketcham

Please see the message below from IVCC for virtual summer camp!

Greetings from Illinois Valley Community College's Continuing Education Center. Beginning in June we are offering virtual classroom camps for youth, ages 8-14, to explore coding, game design, editing, 3D modeling and other STEAM topics from a safe social distance at home. Head to https://blackrocket.com/online/ivc/ to see our virtual camp listing. A printable version, announcing our upcoming art contest, is attached. These popular offerings are now open for online registration.

We are optimistic that as our region re-opens we will be able to offer in-person camp experiences, for small groups, in July & August. Be sure to like our Facebook page for updates: https://www.facebook.com/ivcccebs

Greetings from Illinois Valley Community College's Continuing Education Center. Beginning in June we are offering virtual classroom camps for youth, ages 8-14, to explore coding, game design, editing, 3D modeling and other STEAM topics from a safe social distance at home. Head to https://blackrocket.com/online/ivc/ to see our virtual camp listing. A printable version, announcing our upcoming art contest, is attached. These popular offerings are now open for online registration.

We are optimistic that as our region re-opens we will be able to offer in-person camp experiences, for small groups, in July & August. Be sure to like our Facebook page for updates: https://www.facebook.com/ivcccebs

BLACKROCKET.COM
Illinois Valley Community College | Black Rocket

post_text:
STREATOR HIGH SCHOOL IS HOME TO 2 STATE WINNERS!

Each year, hundreds of Illinois FFA members from 345 Ag Programs within Illinois compete to be named the State Winner. For the second year in a row, Streator is home to not 1 but 2 state winners.

Alea Ogle & Lance Moritz will be recognized as the State Winners at the 2020 State FFA Convention whether it is in person or virtually. They will represent not only Streator but also Illinois as the State Winner at the 2020 National FFA Convention through a national application!

Helena Ogle, also competed as a State Finalist and had an amazing run this year but sadly, was not selected as a state winner. Congratulations to all from Streator Elementary!

post_text:
From Eddie Levy - Parent and Board Member.

THANK YOU to the administrators, teachers, staff, volunteers, students, and parents of Streator Elementary School District #44 for your strength, dedication, and perseverance throughout these abnormal times. You are truly building a better world, one student at a time. I feel so blessed to live in a community that works so hard and cares so much about it‚Äôs children‚Äôs education.

Today‚Äôs news saddens all of us, and while it‚Äôs not the outcome we may have wanted we must understand that these decisions are made with the best interests of the children, faculty, and staff in mind. Please continue to stay strong and persevere through these unprecedented times.

I‚Äôm definitely not any kind of expert. I will be encouraging my kids to talk, journal, use alternative methods to foster relationships and will try to be understanding that we‚Äôre all going through some stuff right now. I will help my kids understand that this will pass and we will carry on stronger for it as we always have and always will.

#StreatorStrong

The District sent a message to all parents and staff this afternoon that Governor Pritzker has extended the stay-at-home order and school closures through April 30th.

This means that ELearning will continue after break. We will prepare for next steps of ELearning on April 14th and 15th and release packets on April 16th. PLEASE come to the school on April 16th and get a packet for your child if you don't print the materials online. This is so important for your child.

As a reminder, there is no instruction during our scheduled spring break, which is set for next week, April 6th through April 13th. Our teachers and staff will be enjoying a much deserved break during that time.

Food deliveries will continue during spring break.

Riley Hintzsche‚ÄéStreator FFA Chapter Friends & Family
March 31 at 6:45 PM ¬∑

So how do these little dudes get out of that egg???

Well, if you look at the tip of this chicks nose you will find what is called the egg tooth. This egg tooth develops while the chick is in the egg and disappears within 5 days after it hatches! It‚Äôs pointy and the chick uses it to peck at the shell until it cracks and then it continues to do this until it‚Äôs able to get out of the egg!

What can I say, chicks are pretty neat!

post_text:
Northlawn Students and Parents -

If you need a paper copy of assignments, they are in marked bins at Northlawn starting today. The bins will remain outside until Monday morning.

Bins are on the north side of the building (entrance across from McDonalds) in grade level order. The 5th grade bin is nearest the 5th grade entrance.

If your child has individualized assignments given in a special education class ( such as Speech, CARES, and Mrs. LeRette‚Äôs classroom), the packets will not be outside. Those packets will be delivered to students soon if you haven't already received them.

We will release information on Centennial and Kimes as we receive it. Please remember everything is also online.

Thank you!!
